const faqs = [
  { q: 'Is the Plugable USB-C Triple 4K Dock better than the CalDigit TS4?', a: 'It depends on your priorities. The Plugable offers triple 4K60 output and 100W charging for $199, which is about $130 less than the CalDigit TS4. The TS4 offers Thunderbolt 4 bandwidth (40 Gbps), more ports, faster data transfer, and a driver-free experience on macOS. If your priority is triple 4K output on a budget, the Plugable wins. If your priority is maximum bandwidth, Thunderbolt 4, and a premium build, the CalDigit TS4 wins.' },
  { q: 'Does the Plugable USB-C Triple 4K Dock work with a Mac?', a: 'Yes, but it requires DisplayLink drivers, which are a kernel extension you install on macOS. Once installed, the dock drives up to three displays on Intel Macs and up to two displays on M1/M2 Macs (the third is capped at 4K30 due to DisplayLink bandwidth limits on Apple Silicon). The driver is free and maintained by Synaptics, but it does add some CPU overhead — roughly 5 to 10% on an M1 Mac under heavy display use.' },
  { q: 'Does the Plugable USB-C Triple 4K Dock require Thunderbolt?', a: 'No. The dock uses DisplayLink technology, not Thunderbolt, so it works with any USB-C port that supports USB 3.2 Gen 2 (10 Gbps) data — including USB-C ports on older laptops that do not have Thunderbolt. This is the main advantage over Thunderbolt docks like the CalDigit TS4, which require a Thunderbolt 3 or 4 port. The trade-off is lower bandwidth: DisplayLink tops out at about 4 Gbps per display, which is enough for 4K60 but not for fast external NVMe SSDs.' },
