        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>The <strong>CalDigit TS4</strong> is the premium alternative at $329. It offers Thunderbolt 4 bandwidth (40 Gbps), 18 ports, a driver-free macOS experience, and native display output that supports two 4K60 displays (or four 4K30 displays with daisy-chaining). It is the better dock if you need maximum bandwidth, fast external NVMe SSDs, or a clean macOS experience. But it costs $130 more and does not support three 4K60 displays without daisy-chaining. See our <a href="/reviews/caldigit-ts4-review/">CalDigit TS4 review</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Anker 564</strong> is the direct competitor at $179 — also a DisplayLink dock with 100W charging. It supports two 4K60 displays (not three), so it is the pick if you only need dual monitors and want to save $20. The build quality is comparable, but the Anker has fewer display outputs and a shorter 1-year warranty. For triple 4K, the Plugable is the only option at this price.</p>

      <p>The <strong>Satechi Thunderbolt 4 Dock</strong> is the Thunderbolt alternative at $299. It offers two 4K60 displays over native Thunderbolt (no DisplayLink driver), 96W charging, and a clean aluminum design. It is the pick if you want Thunderbolt 4 but do not need the CalDigit TS4's full port selection. Like the CalDigit, it caps at two 4K60 displays — the Plugable is the only dock here that does three.</p>

      <p>Pair the Plugable with the right <a href="/reviews/best-standing-desk-under-300/">standing desk</a> — a multi-monitor rig needs a stable, spacious surface, and the <a href="/reviews/flexispot-e7-review/">FlexiSpot E7</a> is our pick for a desk that holds a dock and three monitors without wobble.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the UD-ULTC4K if you need three 4K displays from a single dock and you want to spend less than $250. It is the only dock at this price that drives triple 4K60, and the 100W charging and 10 ports cover most productivity use cases. For Windows users with USB-C laptops, it is a near-perfect value.</p>

      <p>Check your laptop charging wattage first. The 100W Power Delivery is enough for most 13- and 14-inch laptops, but 15- and 16-inch laptops under load can exceed 100W. If your laptop draws more than 100W, the dock will still drive your displays and peripherals, but your laptop may discharge slowly under sustained load. For 16-inch MacBook Pros and high-end gaming laptops, look for a dock with 140W or higher charging.</p>

      <p>Install the DisplayLink driver before you plug in. On Windows, grab the latest driver from Synaptics (not Plugable — Plugable links to the same Synaptics installer). On macOS, install the driver, reboot, and approve the kernel extension in Privacy & Security. Doing this before you connect the dock saves a confusing first-hour of troubleshooting.</p>

      <p>Skip the UD-ULTC4K if you need Thunderbolt 4 bandwidth. DisplayLink is fine for productivity displays, but it is not fast enough for external NVMe SSDs running at full speed. If you edit video on an external Thunderbolt SSD, the CalDigit TS4 (40 Gbps) is the dock you want — the Plugable's 10 Gbps USB connection will bottleneck your storage.</p>

      <p>Skip it on macOS if you want a driver-free experience. DisplayLink on macOS works, but it adds a kernel extension and CPU overhead that native Thunderbolt avoids. If you have a Thunderbolt 4 Mac and you only need two 4K displays, a native Thunderbolt dock like the CalDigit TS4 or the Satechi Thunderbolt 4 Dock is the cleaner choice. If you need three displays on an M-series Mac, you are stuck with DisplayLink — and the Plugable is the best of the DisplayLink docks.</p>

      <p>Buy a <a href="/reviews/best-cable-management-desk/">cable management</a> solution at the same time. A dock with 10 ports generates a lot of cables, and without routing they will tangle behind your desk. A simple under-desk cable tray and some velcro straps take 20 minutes to install and keep the dock's outputs organized.</p>

